message.content:
Sorry for the misunderstanding, but the bytecode you provided is the compiled result of a Solidity smart contract. It's not possible to revert it back to the original Solidity source code directly. The bytecode is a low-level language that the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) understands, while Solidity is a high-level language that developers use to write smart contracts.

However, you can use a decompiler to get a high-level pseudocode representation of the contract, but it won't be the original Solidity code. Tools such as etherscan.io provide this service. 

If the contract is verified on etherscan, you can actually see the original Solidity code. If not, you can only see the decompiled pseudocode or assembly code.
